After its capture, it was used by the U.S. as an emergency landing site for B-29s, which eventually made 2,900 emergency landings there that are estimated to have saved the lives of 24,000 airmen who would have otherwise had to crash at sea.

Twenty-seven Medals of Honor were awarded for action in the battle, more than any other in U.S. military history.

The only surviving Medal of Honor recipient from Iwo Jima, Hershel 'Woody' Williams, 91, attended the ceremony. 

Afterward, he said his feelings toward the Japanese had not changed in the decades since the battle.

'They were just doing their jobs, just like we were,' he said. 'We tried to kill them before they could kill us. But that's war.'

